Probably not &quot;directly&quot;, since that would mean grandma would hav=
e to have quite an understanding of digital encoding, including which bits =
mean what, when, and where.  But even on a digital recorder, there is still=
 an analog element (the Analog to Digital converter) which takes the sound =
pressure waves, as represented by some analog electronic detection element,=
 and converts that into digital.  That way, long departed uncle Ebenezer do=
es not need to do anything digital.  Under this scenario, if sound is not b=
eing heard in the room, but is being induced into the circuitry, then it wo=
uld be round about that AtoD converter (assuming it isn&#39;t other just plain =
old noise in the digital elements).  

Someone with more electronic know-ho=
w than me might be able to better pinpoint the area in the analog portion o=
f that AtoD pipeline where it would be most likely it could be influenced b=
y, say, an EM field, and that would also occur in a normal analog tape reco=
rder.


